##ABSTRACT

This document is a report of Team Project of EECS4415 Big Data System Fall 2018. The project involves defining a problem, understanding the storage and processing needs (short term and long term) of a big data analytics solution and select an appropriate technical approach.

This project analyzes csv files of &quot;Python Questions from Stack Overflow&quot;


, digging deeper into the relationship between the answer and the respondent in a Spark and MapReduce environment. We split up the analyze process into two parts. Part A, we link up the tags of the questions and the corresponding respondent and sort out the most important tags for each respondent. Part B, we analyze each of the answers&#39; text body and determine the key words so that identify a most important words list for each respondent. By working through these approaches, we are able to build a dataset to determine the areas of expertise of each respondent and suggest experts from existing users for further incoming questions.

In this paper, we describe Motivation, Data and Data Analysis, Architecture of Proposed Solution, Evaluation/Result, and Conclusion.

##KEYWORDS

Big data, HDFS, Spark, Python, TF-IDF

1 Introduction and Motivation

1.1 Introduction

This project is about to aggregate two tables, question-answer table and question-tags table, by finding the key words of each respondent so that we can build up a profile for each on them to identify their expertise areas. The resulting dataset can be served as an experts list to suggest experts for further incoming questions. This process includes two parts: A, find out the top tags for every respondent based on their answered questions&#39; tags. B, calculate their answered text to sort out a keywords list for each respondent.

##1.2 Data Domain



We choose to use the csv file of &quot;Python Questions from Stack Overflow&quot; which contains full text of Stack Overflow Q&amp;A about the Python programming language from kaggel.com

 as our fundamental dataset for analyzing existing answers.

We use two csv under the website, Answer.csv and Tags.csv. For each record in an Answer.csv, we use the &quot;OwnerUserId&quot;, &quot;ParentId&quot; and &quot;Body&quot; where the &quot;ParentId&quot; refers to a question id. For each record in Tags.csv, we use all columns where the &quot;ID&quot; refers to a question id.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Figure 1:structure of &quot;Python Questions from Stack Overflow&quot; csv files.

##1.3 Goals, Motivation and Importance of Analysis


Our goal is to calculate the key technical words based on tags and keywords in their answered text for each question and group them by owner IDs, therefore generate a list of users with their top important tags based on their answered questions.

With this rigorous data analytics, we are able to identify the areas of expertise of each respondent. This makes it easy to recommend &quot;experts&quot; in related fields for new questions. Without this process, the original dataset does not have more information about answerer apart from their answered text, makes it intricate to group respondent. Our motivation is to build such a relationship to give every respondent a profile to identify their expertise areas.

##1.4 Questions We Want To Answer

The question we are going to answer is that for a new question posted, what are the existing users we can suggest to answer this question. To answer this question, we first have to answer, what are specialties of each respondent we have.

##1.5 Application



With our analytics, we are able to build an off-line recommender system such that for any arbitrary input pure text questions related to Python, provide a list of &quot;experts&quot; those who frequently answer questions on this field.

2 Data and Data Analysis

**2.1 Data Dimensions and Processing Dimensions**

**2.2 Pre-process**

After we picked the dataset which we want to use, we start to preprocess the dataset. We have built a python script to help us retrieve the dataset from Kaggle. Inside the python script, we configured our Kaggle login credentials and import requests library to help us finish the data ingestion process. You could simply run our python script to get the datasets download to your local machine directly.

**2.3 Data Cleaning and Data Transformation**

Since we got two separate and unstructured datasets tag and answers, we need to implement the data cleaning and data transformation processes to make sure our datasets are well organized with error free and get ready for further analytic works.

For data cleaning part, the body column which inside answers.csv is pretty messy. It was built in HTML format with massive code example and special characters. We use serval steps to implement the data cleaning process:

1. We applied regular expression to remove all HTML tags, numbers, code examples, punctuations and meaningless single characters.
2. We import nltk library to remove stop-words.
3. We import pandas library to reconstruct the dataset as a dataframe, and drop the rows that has no Id value.

For data transformation, we use serval steps to implement the data transformation process:

1. In order to find out the top tags for every respondents based on their answered questions&#39; tags, we need to make a join between tag.csv and answers.csv, merge them together to retrieve the data that we need
2. After we load the dataset into a dataframe, we add some new columns on the dataframe to help us analyze the dataset. For instance, we load answers.csv as a dataframe, add new column-distance to store the cosine distance. In this way, we can simply sort and compare the distance column to get the most experienced User Id.

**2.4 Data Analytics Method and Types**

**2.4.1 Use of TFIDF to get keyword**

After the pre-processing process, we get all words which related to our data analysis, i.e, words related to the Python language. We process those word using tf-idf, which is a method for evaluating the importance of words on this file. The formula of tf-idf is as follows

tfidfi,j=tfi,j×log(Ndfi,j)

Where j represent the file index, and i represent the index of a word in the specific file

tfi,j
 indicates the frequency of word with the index of i in the jth file.

dfi,j
 represents the total number of files which containing the word with index of i in the jth file.

If the tf value of a word is higher, it means that word is more important in a document. Meanwhile, if the idf of a word is higher, the frequency of that word appearing in other files is lower. That is, the more specific to this File. So the higher the value of tf-idf, the more critical the word is in this file.

**2.4.2 Use of Cosine Similarity to get a similarity of the current question with profile of &quot;expert&quot;**

        After we find all the keywords of the question which user asked, we need to recommend the &quot;experts&quot; with respect to this questions. We recommend the best &quot;experts&quot; to this questions by evaluating the _cosine similarity_ between questions that a user just asked, to the person who answer questions with a mostly same set of keyword. Cosine similarity is an analysis of the similarity between documents. The formula is as follows

Cosinesimilarity=cosθ=∑i=1n(ai×bi)∑i=1nai2×∑i=1nbi2

Where file A={a1,a2…an}, which ai is the term frequency of ith keyword inside file A

File B={b1,b2…bn}, which bi is the term frequency of ith keyword inside file B

If file A and file B have higher Cosine similarity, then means those two files are more similar. Through the above method, after a question is being asked, we first use the tf-idf mentioned above to find the keyword of the question and generate the word frequency array of the question, and then compute the cosine similarity for this question with profiles of each user inside stack overflow, to find people who answered similar questions before, to give the best 10 &quot;experts&quot; for this problem to consumer.

**2.4.3 Type of**  **data analysis**  **performed**

        The approach we used on our analysis is Descriptive analysis, this analysis answer the question of what happened. To use this type of data analysis, we can get a set of people who might have similar field of study and answered similar questions before. We describe the characteristics of data to calculating and analyzing the data by using tf-idf to analyze the keywords of data, and use Cosine similarity to analyze the degree of similarity between coming data to existing data and generate the expected result.

5 Conclusions

1. Step by step through the two analytics way, we are finally able to build the proposed respondent profiles. We figured out a list of important words that best describe the areas of expertise for every respondent.
2. Reviewing our design, there are several points that we think can be considered as highlights. One is using Spark to do all the MapReduce process. It accelerates the MapReduce process thanks to its in-memory processing compares to Hadoop and its on-disk processing.

 Another highlight is we use Cosine Similarity to find out the most relevant experts. Early on we were using Jaccard Index to find similarity and frequently get unexpected values. Then we look at Cosine Similarity, it fits better in our use case consider the we are mining context in a text body and we only need the index for sorting rather than exact right value.
3. In the future, if we have more time working on this project, we can do better on improving correctness and efficiency. So far what we calculated for the keywords from text body is still not one hundred percent technical, we still need a better way to filter out all common English words or get an accurate technical words list to get more accurate and consistent result. For the efficiency, integrating Elasticsearch is the best way to reduce the waiting time of calculating all the similarities. Since we designed a web server that allows individual clients to search experts, each request triggers a Cosine Similarity process which can be handled by an Elasticsearch server, brings a real-time fast and consistent reach result. Unfortunately, we do not have enough time to work with these features in this project due to the limited time.
